 early modern urban discourse increasingly moves from oral discussion to take the form of writing. And while the dominant tone of those who wrote about cities continued to be one of celebration and glorification, over time a more detached and less judgmental mode developed. More and more they came to see their fundamental task as presenting a description that was objective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aCities and townszEuropexHistoryxSources. 0aCities and towns-Europe-History-Sources. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aCity and town lifezEuropexHistoryxSources. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aArchitecture, Early modern Europe, History, Italy, Spain, Travel writing, Urban history, Urban studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2019z978311078051240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963732654740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789637326547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789637326547/original  a978-3-11-078051-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK